<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="25" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="25">
This new species is introduced as molecular data, and shows it to be a distinct clade with high support (ML/BI = 100/1) and appears closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Diaporthaceae" genus="Diaporthe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Diaporthe hongkongensis" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="hongkongensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Diaporthe hongkongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. M. Tian &amp; Q. Yang" authorityYear="2022" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Diaporthaceae" genus="Diaporthe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Diaporthe rhodomyrti" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="rhodomyrti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Diaporthe rhodomyrti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished based on ITS, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">cal</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">his3</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">tef-1α</emphasis>
, and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">tub2</emphasis>
loci from 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. hongkongensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="hongkongensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">D. hongkongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(2/463 in ITS, 26/441 in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">cal</emphasis>
, 11/434 in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">his3</emphasis>
, 10/327 in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">tef-1α</emphasis>
, and 2/420 in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">tub2</emphasis>
). Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. rhodomyrti" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="rhodomyrti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">D. rhodomyrti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. hongkongensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="hongkongensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">D. hongkongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its longer conidiogenous cells (15.5-23 vs. 5-12 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) and narrower beta conidia (1-1.5 vs. 1.5-2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3767/003158513X666844" author="Gomes, RR" journalOrPublisher="Persoonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 41" refId="B13" refString="Gomes, RR, Glienke, C, Videira, SIR, Lombard, L, Groenewald, JZ, Crous, PW, 2013. Diaporthe: A genus of endophytic, saprobic and plant pathogenic fungi. Persoonia 31 (1): 1 - 41, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3767/003158513X666844" title="Diaporthe: A genus of endophytic, saprobic and plant pathogenic fungi." url="https://doi.org/10.3767/003158513X666844" volume="31" year="2013">Gomes et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). This is the first time that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nitschke &amp; Pyrenomyc.Germ" authorityYear="1870" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Diaporthaceae" genus="Diaporthe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Diaporthe" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Diaporthe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species has been discovered from infected leaves on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Rhodomyrtus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rhodomyrtus tomentosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Rhodomyrtus tomentosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and demonstrate it as a new species based on phylogeny and morphology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
